Plain English Explanation

This theory suggests that dark matter may not just be invisible “stuff” sitting around galaxies passively.

Instead, dark matter could come from a hidden Higgs-like field that naturally forms structured pathways through space, somewhat similar mathematically to how proteins and muscles organise, strengthen, and repair themselves inside the body.

The idea is not that dark matter is literally biological protein.
Rather, it behaves in a “protein-like” way by:

- self-organising into stable structures,
- reinforcing frequently used pathways,
- repairing disrupted regions,
- and adapting over time to repeated galactic motion.

In this model:

- galaxies move partly because of gravity,
- and partly because stars travel within these reinforced invisible pathways.

The theory still keeps dark matter as real unseen mass, so it can still explain gravitational lensing and other observations that require additional gravity.

A key feature of the framework is that the adaptive behaviour mainly becomes important after galaxies form. In the early universe, the hidden field behaves much more like ordinary cold dark matter, helping preserve compatibility with existing cosmology observations.

The theory also makes a testable prediction:

«galaxies with stronger organised magnetic or pathway structure should show different unexplained rotational behaviour compared with galaxies where that structure is weaker or disrupted.»

If future observations or simulations show this correlation exists, it could support the idea that dark matter behaves as a self-organising hidden structure rather than a purely passive invisible halo.
